title: Modify Pipeline Facilities to Fix PipeDream Deadlock
body:
In our current design, one pipeline stage may compute
`Wait->Recv->FW->Send->Record`
and then
`Wait->Recv->BW->Send->Record`
However, this may have a deadlock. To resolve it, we need to do
`Wait->Recv->Wait->FW->Record->Send->Record`
and then
`Wait->Recv->Wait->BW->Record->Send->Record`

This PR changes pipeline transformation for adding extra `Wait`s and `Record`s. In addition, to avoid another GPU deadlock, we move `Send` and `Recv` to CPU completely. We also fix the shape inference in `WaitEvent`/`RecordEvent`. It wrongly passed **unknown shape** to **scalar shape** from input to output.

title: Function expansion support and Update ONNX to 1.7 release candidate 1.
body:
Motivation for this change:
  - In preparation for ORT 1.3 release we must make it compliant with ONNX 1.7.
  - Function expansion support for functions that require context and bug fixes in this area that were failing most ONNX function expansion test.
    - Prerequisite for ORT 1.3 release to be compliant with functions.

4. One loop run will always succeed, the success of next runs depend on whether they get the same thread from thread pool. If not, the program crashes.

title: Fix flaky test and avoid divide by zero in SoftmaxCrossEntropyLoss-CPU.
body:
The change fixes two issues that were caught as _flaky_ test:

1. **Invalid label data being passed into tests**
    - `random.Uniform` returns values that are outside the range [a, b) because of `float` to `int64` cast internally due to the usage of `uniform_real_distribution` that expects template type of floating types only. This results in index out of bounds exception when we use `uniform_real_distribution` with `std::default_random_engine` and perform an explicit cast from `float` to `int64`. We must have an overload of  `random.Uniform` that uses `uniform_int_distribution` to prevent the need for such a cast.

2. **SoftmaxCrossEntropyLoss-CPU dividing by zero**
    - One of the test was exercising the scenario where all label values were `0` and `ignore_index` was also `0` hence the loss should also be zero since all values should be dropped. On GPU the kernel correctly calculated loss as zero but on CPU it ended up dividing sum of all losses (zero) by zero which resulted in -nan.

Interestingly, both the tests ran fine on Windows even when I ran them in a loop for 100 times. In the hindsight, it seems this issue also existed in _GatherGradOpTest.Gather_axis1_float_impl2_ and _GatherGradOpTest.Gather_axis0_float_impl2_ that I have fixed as part of this PR.
